AGI - Waiting for a response from Hamas on the last proposed truce submitted by the mediators in Cairo, Israel continues to look at Rafah. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, in a meeting with relatives of the hostages and the fallen, reiterated the intention to launch the invasion of land against the city in the far south of Gaza, despite the harsh opposition of the United States. "We will enter Rafah and annihilate all Hamas battalions there, with or without an agreement, to achieve total victory," said the head of government.&nbsp; "The idea that we will end the war before reaching all our objectives is unacceptable," he said. The armed forces (Idf) have announced that the 98th and 162th Army division have carried out intensive preparations for future offensives in the Strip, including the imminent operation at Rafah. "The division commanders have completed the approval of plans for the next missions and are continuing to increase their preparation." According to the Israeli media, if a hostage agreement with Hamas will not be reached within the next few days, the operation will begin.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
A high official has made it clear that the Israeli executive will wait until tomorrow evening a response from the Palestinian group before deciding whether to send or not sent to Cairo for talks on the ceasefire.<br> Against the last draft agreement the Israeli Finance Minister and leader of the extreme right Bezalel Smotrich has hurled: "Whoever will contribute, will be remembered forever in the history of the Jewish State, and does not deserve to be considered his leader," said Knesset. For the leader of religious Zionism, "the Egyptian proposal is a terrible defeat and defeat of the Blue and White Party (led by Benny Gantz, minister in the war cabinet, ed.) that will give Hamas a clamorous victory over a silver plate". Smotrich accused the war cabinet of "accepting strategic concessions that jeopardize the State of Israel" and urged Netanyahu to "do not wave white flag, do not let Sinwar still humiliate us and win the war".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, the Hamas delegation left Cairo to return to Qatar and "discuss the proposal". The intention, he added a source is to respond as quickly as possible. On the table there would be a plan for a ceasefire of 40 days and the release of dozens of hostages in exchange for a number of Palestinian prisoners. According to Egyptian sources, Hamas envoys should "go back with a written answer". After Riad, continues the regional tour of the American Secretary of State Antony Blinken, who before landing in Israel stopped in Amman for talks with King Abdallah II and Jordanian Foreign Minister Ayman Safadi focusing on diplomatic efforts to increase humanitarian aid to the Strip and end the war in Gaza.
